Patch Set 7:

The existing functional tests does not accommodate changes to exit codes. And, an attempt to edit them to reflect the updated exits results in segmentation faults. Not sure how we can do an exit 1 in this case.. (re-raising an exception does not work too) Maybe that is why the existing code just does an LOG.error and not exit 1?
Any suggestions or ideas?

Patch Set 7:

Provided a patch via paste out of band with an alternate means of addressing this, with all tests passing to give some ideas. 

The other functional tests which are failing when this bug is fixed are failing because an invalid configuration for the scrubber is provided and when the functional test suite tries to start the scrubber in a background process the scrubber (correctly) exits with an exit code 1, which violates an implicit expectation of those tests (an expectation baked into the start_servers method). It becomes necessary to revise some tests at least a bit because of this flaw in the functional test framework.

In each case I found that the scrubber was not needed by the tests and by even attempting to start it we were adding a significant amount of time to test execution time. 

My patch bypasses the startup (and shutdown) of the scrubber for those tests via a newly supported conditional exclusion of the scrubber introduced to the FunctionalTest class. This also cuts significant time from test execution. 

Other potential solutions exist, including setting the expected exit code for the scrubber process before starting services.
Uploaded patch set 8.

Patch Set 8:

Uploaded PS #8 after editing functional test cases with Steve's guidance.
Since spawn_n is used in daemon_mode, as per [1], we need not have additional conditional checks to determine whether to raise and exception or exit, as spawn handles that for the daemon mode automatically.
[1] http://eventlet.net/doc/modules/greenthread.html#eventlet.greenthread.spawn_n

Patch Set 14:

I recommended defaulting the Scrubber to enabled in functional tests, and only disabled it (set it to False) in cases where a) it was clear that the scrubber was NOT needed for the functional use case and b) the scrubber was unable to find the registry service (often due to misconfiguration), causing the non-zero exit and the test suite failure.

We could switch it the other way but I was concerned that future contributors may not realize they needed to explicitly enable the scrubber in a functional scenario which did rely on the scrubber. It was exactly the concern about missing it out that I felt recommended a default True.

I don't feel really strongly about that decision, and have no qualms about adding more comments as guidance.
